{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530634"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:09:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:09:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14557"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14557"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.16,0.34,0.41,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56909"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7250"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42363"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"133"},{"type":"tags","id":"571"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56909"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man was admitted to the intensive care unit three days ago with a delayed presentation following drug overdose. He has no significant medical history and takes no known medications.\u003Cbr /\u003EOn review today, his clinical state is noted to be worsening. He is increasingly confused and agitated, disoriented to time and place with slurred speech. He appears to be oedematous and covered in bruises, and during the review he has a large episode of haematemesis. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following drugs is most likely to have caused this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diazepam","Ibuprofen","Aspirin","Paracetamol","Codeine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clinical picture consistent with fulminant liver failure, likely due to drug-induced hepatotoxicity. The most likely causative agent in this scenario is \u003Cstrong\u003Eparacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E. Paracetamol overdose is one of the most common causes of acute liver failure in many countries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features suggestive of fulminant liver failure in this case include progressive confusion and agitation (hepatic encephalopathy) and signs of impaired liver synthetic function, such as bruising and haematemesis, which indicate coagulopathy. The oedema suggests hypoalbuminaemia, another complication of liver failure. The progression from initial presentation to severe hepatic dysfunction over a few days is characteristic of paracetamol toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E (acetylsalicylic acid) overdose can cause metabolic acidosis and respiratory alkalosis but does not typically cause this degree of liver failure. It can cause mild to moderate elevations in liver enzymes, but not the severe synthetic dysfunction seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIbuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID), can cause gastric irritation and renal impairment in overdose, but severe hepatotoxicity is rare. It would not typically cause the degree of liver dysfunction and encephalopathy seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECodeine\u003C/strong\u003E overdose primarily causes central nervous system and respiratory depression. While it can cause mild transaminitis, it does not typically lead to fulminant liver failure with hepatic encephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E, a benzodiazepine, primarily causes central nervous system depression in overdose. It is not hepatotoxic and would not cause the liver failure and associated complications seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly recognition of paracetamol overdose is crucial, as timely administration of the antidote N-acetylcysteine can prevent or mitigate liver damage. However, once fulminant liver failure develops, as in this case, management focuses on supportive care and potentially liver transplantation if indicated. The progression of hepatic encephalopathy and worsening synthetic liver function over days following the overdose is a hallmark of severe paracetamol-induced liver failure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paracetamol overdose is a common cause of fulminant liver failure.","Signs of fulminant liver failure include coagulopathy and hepatic encephalopathy.","Early recognition and treatment of paracetamol overdose is crucial to prevent liver failure.","Hepatic encephalopathy can present with a range of neurological symptoms, from subtle confusion to coma."],"references":["Agrawal S, Khazaeni B. Acetaminophen Toxicity. [Updated 2023 Jun 9]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441917/","Chiew, A.L., Reith, D., Pomerleau, A., Wong, A., Isoardi, K.Z., Soderstrom, J. and Buckley, N.A. (2020), Updated guidelines for the management of paracetamol poisoning in Australia and New Zealand. Med. J. Aust., 212: 175-183. https://doi.org/10.5694/mja2.50428","Shah NJ, Royer A, John S. Acute Liver Failure. [Updated 2023 Apr 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482374/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42363"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14557"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42363"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-22T14:30:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T14:31:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7250"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical stu